    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1977-07-08T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1977-07-08T00:00:00-05:00" n="349"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d349">
                <head>349. Memorandum From Secretary of State <persName corresp="#p_VCR_1"
                        >Vance</persName> to President <persName corresp="#p_CJE_1"
                        >Carter</persName>
                    <note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d349fn1">Source: Carter Library, National
                        Security Affairs, <persName corresp="#p_BZ_1">Brzezinski</persName>
                        Material, Country File, Box 22, France: 1–12/77. Secret. In the upper
                        right-hand corner of the first page of the memorandum, <persName
                            corresp="#p_CJE_1">Carter</persName> wrote “Cy, J.”</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1977-07-08">July 8, 1977</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>[Omitted here is material unrelated to non-proliferation.]</p>
                <p>4. <hi rend="italic">
                        <persName corresp="#p_SG_1">Gerard Smith</persName>’s Meetings in
                        Paris:</hi>
                    <persName corresp="#p_SG_1">Gerard Smith</persName> has just completed an
                    initial day of consultations in Paris with Foreign Minister <persName
                        corresp="#p_GLD_1">de Guiringaud</persName> and other key officials on
                    non-proliferation and nuclear policy questions.<note n="2" xml:id="d349fn2">The
                        Embassy transmitted a report of the meeting in telegram 19861 from Paris,
                        July 8. (National Archives, <gloss target="#t_RG_1">RG</gloss> 59, Central
                        Foreign Policy Files, D770243–0334)</note> The French reiterated strongly
                    the importance they attach to their present nuclear power program.<note n="3"
                        xml:id="d349fn3">In the left-hand margin, <persName corresp="#p_CJE_1"
                            >Carter</persName> wrote “We’ll form a policy, along with others, either
                        with or without the French.”</note>
                </p>
                <p>The discussion produced understandings on spent fuel retransfers, and on
                    renegotiation of the US/EURATOM agreement. The understandings remove these
                    issues as impediments to French participation in the International Nuclear Fuel
                    Cycle Evaluation (<gloss target="#t_INFCE_1">INFCE</gloss>). However, the French
                    indicated great distress over Canada’s insistence that it have a veto over
                    reprocessing of any fuel Canada supplies. It is not yet clear whether the French
                    participation in <gloss target="#t_INFCE_1">INFCE</gloss> will be conditioned on
                    solution of this problem. The French government will make its decision after the
                    next experts meeting, now scheduled for the end of July.</p>
                <p>Ambassador <persName corresp="#p_SG_1">Smith</persName> also reiterated our
                    concern over the reprocessing plant sale to Pakistan and our interest in
                    full-scope safeguards. There is no new French position on these issues yet.</p>
                <p>[Omitted here is material unrelated to non-proliferation.]</p>
            </div>
